reviewText: This movie will touch your very heart!  I saw it and was so moved I just sat there for several minutes after it was over just reveling in the good feelings!

This movie is such a wonderful cinematic experience for Christians and non-Christians alike. The supremely talented and beautiful AJ Michalka delivers an absolutely draw-you-in performance as Grace, an 18-year-old singer whose relationship with God is put to the ultimate test when she flies out to Hollywood to try to become the chart-topping superstar she's always dreamed of being. Along the way she endures a number of pitfalls and faces the ultimate challenge or either giving up her Christian faith entirely or rediscovering it for the good of her family. Whether you truly believe in God and the effort He puts into keeping us all safe or just want to watch a great movie, you will not be disappointed one bit by this enormously heartwarming and inspiring story of finding the right path to take and knowing what the Lord Himself has in mind for you. Grace Unplugged is seriously a phenomenal film that you must see and share with all your loved ones.

Good pacing; storyline pretty good; in-depth characterization; some dynamic changes; acting and dialogue OK but improve dramatically as the story continues. The difficult trick with Christian movies is that they often fall into didactic (or preachy) dialogue, although sometimes that would be realistic; there's some of that here but it's much more tolerable (and sounds less self-righteous) than in other movies of type and genre. As a musician, I wish they would have explored the differences between worship and entertainment and motive a little more, since that is an interesting subject that was glanced upon. The true heart of the film REALLY is shown and not told, which is good, but may have been amplified a bit more. OVERALL, a really good movie that is worth seeing.

I am always on the lookout for well-made Christian films. While this one is by no means perfect, it is better than many out there. It is rather cliche and predictable, and some of the scenes are overexposed, but I was still completely engaged with the characters and the story. It is a movie I will be keeping on my shelf and watching again. I was teary-eyed and worshiping and caused me to thank God once again for His grace in my own life. HOWEVER, when I watch this film again I will be stopping it before the last five minutes, which left me feeling a bit cheated. It was like they were presenting a good message and then backpedaled. I would still recommend the movie, whether you watch the last five minutes or not. It's not terrible and may prompt discussion, but I was sad it was included as I felt it was out of place and shallow.
*Spoiler*
The movie would have had a more powerful ending without the "2 years later" part. Either that, or change what happened 2 years later (for example, if Grace had continued to be a music teacher, or some other less glamorous but respectable pursuit). Not that you can't be a recording artist and following the Lord, but the end was too neatly packaged: "Look, you can have Jesus AND be a star!". It would have been nice to see her choose to use her talents to magnify the Lord without being in the limelight.

This movie feels a a bit like a good made for TV movie and although not every movie can be at the top of the charts I always welcome good stories and faith-based movies and feel they do very well given the lack of major Hollywood backing. I give it 3.5 stars for good values and a good common story of real life and learning for oneself. I recommend it but it's just not the best movie made to deserve 5 stars.

*(These next two paragraphs were copied directly from the movie site, as it summarizes it best)
"Having just turned 18, Grace Trey aspires to more than just singing at her church, where the worship leader is her fathera former pop star. So, with the help of Mossy, her dad's former manager, Grace records a cover version of her dad's old Top-10 hit, runs off to Los Angeles, and begins to taste the kind of stardom she's always dreamed about."

"Yet with each rung of the ladder she climbs, Grace feels more and more pressure to compromise her values, further straining her relationship with her parents. Will everything she experiences lead her to reject her faith  or rediscover it?"

Real life inspirational stories honestly portray relationships with others AND ourselves and this movie reflects how many times we want to overly protect others from making mistakes when more often we ourselves know people learn best from personal experience. The irony is, being overly-protective and without good communication with those we care about, people often drive the one they are trying to protect to having to prove for themselves the very thing they were intended to avoid in the first place.

It tells of the importance of not giving up our personal ideals, religious or not, for the thing we desire most, like "rock star" image and life. Most children in today's society dream of the rock star image without understanding worldy influence and consequences they WILL have to face. More often then not, media only focuses on the occasional bliss and not the realities most often faced in life.

The story also portrays the lack of communication between parents and their children and the difficulty of having to let children experience trials on their own, as we all learn better from hands-on experience. As with the father in this movie, parents often force rules without explaining their personal experience and foreseen consequences, so children can't grasp the whole picture and can't understand the rules and the truth of their parents' love. How can we truly expect another to understand our own conclusion without explaining the problem and work it took to get there. Can we really expect to give an answer with an algebraic equation without first teaching the process?

Some reviews complained the movie strayed too far from presenting the gospel, which I did feel lacking in the beginning, however I soon realized it was not intended to teach about the gospel as one story teller understands it, but allows the movie to appeal to a wider audience, since we all believe and understand differently, especially youth. If you had expectation of a story about a Christian including more gospel truth, just remember even parables are stories about truths which help inspire us even though they don't spell out the Christian gospel at all.

If we have true conviction we should not give up our personal beliefs for fame and money and we can each be happy and successful in our own way.

I really liked this movie and it was the 2nd time watching it.  I thought it dealt with the issue of young adult children wanting to pursue their own dreams even if they were contrary to what their parents wanted for them, especially when the dreams might have many unhealthy consequences. It showed real life emotions on both sides.  Because biblical values were taught and practiced in the home the young woman had a strong foundation about following a plan for her life that God would bless. Still, she wanted to spread her wings and follow her dreams anyway, and she did. The way the parents dealt with the situation, after some of their own soul searching and asking God for help, showed their unconditional love for her and that their hearts were always open to her.
Eventually, after some trial and error, and the support of a new friend, Grace's eyes were open and she understood for herself where God would truly fulfill her dreams.

My hubby and I LOVED this film. Grace, like many teenagers, is rebelling. Her dad is a little too hard on her which makes the rebellion even worse. When a music producer comes to Johnny and asks if he will go on tour with a remastered version of his hit song, Misunderstood, from many years ago, he declines as he believes the Lord has him in the right place and his life has changed since then.

Grace, who has been leading worship with her dad, goes behind her parents back and agrees to do the song. Boy, is she in for a shock. She can definitely sing but is SO naive about other parts of life and how people in the music industry work.

Watch this movie to see how God protects Grace and eventually brings redemption and forgiveness, restoring her relationship with the Lord and her family. Yes, Johnny repents also as she sees the mistakes he has made.

Grace is a young woman who goes out on her own at 18 to find out the real world may not be all she thought it would be.  She began her singing career in church, singing with her father on the worship team.  There are plans in the works to release a Christian CD; but her dad seems to be holding her back regarding her talent.  Its not until he releases her to God that he realizes her talent and allows God to work in her life.

As parents its a fine line to walk ... raising our children and then allowing them to make decisions on their own.  Trusting that they listened to us and are capable of making the right decisions. Yet, wanting your 18 year old daughter to go out into the music industry by herself is definitely a parent's right to be concerned.

Rebellion is part of growing up.
Giving our children back to God is tough (actually they are His and He has loaned them to us).
Reaching the breaking point, falling on our knees and allowing God to take control, priceless.

Grace unplugged was a  great film that talks about what happens when your value system gets challenged by fame and success in the music industry. It also shows how the music industry moulds people into saleable items. This story shows when one very talented musician / vocalist named Grace feels limited in her music with her father. When her father is asked to make a comeback from a very successful song, he declines because it almost ruined his life. His daughter records the track with her feel in it, sends it to the record company and is accepted to come and record the song. At the same time her relationship with her father begins to breaks down.  Grace decides to go to LA and make it big.  However she finds very quickly that she is constantly being moulded by her manager and the record company.  All of this confronts her into making  choices that may compromise her faith while opening her eyes to the world of the music industry.  Without saying much more, this is a great movie to see and a very real picture of what can and has happened to many talented musos in the recording industry.

AJ Michalka, James Denton, Kevin Pollack, Shawnee Smith, and Michael Welch all did an excellent job with the roles they were given. The inspirational music fit the story and advanced the plot. The "owning your faith" message was presented without being too heavy-handed or preachy. However, [SPOILER] the takeaway for the viewer at the end of the movie is this: if you stand up for your faith, then you can be a minor Christian celebrity. This was certainly reinforced by the Chris Tomlin cameo. In this regard, the movie falls into the familiar Christian cinematic trappings of wrapping up complicated issues with a tidy bow as everyone ends up with a happy ending.

Got together with our friends and re-watched about the last half of the movie (to refresh our memories). Were coming to the spot where it stopped before and were all kind of holding our breath. It reached the same point and sort of " jumped" or paused very briefly - like half second, but then went on. We all just looked at each other when it paused but got a big laugh when it continued. I didn't catch the location number, but it's right after Grace & Quentin are on the beach, then get up and are walking away and Quentin is telling her, basically, what she needs to hear. I am sorry, but I must have been out of the room when the term "Christian" was re-defined. To be a Christian is to be one who's been to the foot of the cross in the realization that one is a sinner and that nothing short of repentance of that sin and full and unequivocal surrender to the person of Jesus Christ will ever do in the life from that moment on. It means a life changed and forever after sold out to the Lord Jesus in everything. It means a great deal more than the few paltry statements of pure unadulterated lip service that are contained in this film.

Being a follower of Jesus is more than playing the latest contemporary music in a church worship team, it means being his, twenty four seven, in all that we do. Walking in ways that please Him not striving to have one's way because it satisfies the flesh. There is never any indication that the young lady in this film, or her father either, have got any more than a "little religion" which has made them somewhat different from those around them.

The new birth, regeneration, as specified by Jesus in John 3, and later in the NT in the book of Titus is a whole new way of life, because it's life that God has given not simply a new way of doing things. "Christian" films today are marginalizing what it means to be a child of the King. And it's so disappointing to see professing Christian brethren give them high marks simply because sex and bad language are being omitted. Our standards are being lowered each time a film of this genre makes its appearance.

My family and I thoroughly enjoyed this movie, great singing, great story line, we are probably going to buy it now!!  Loved it
Really enjoyed this gentle reminder of what God's plans are for us.  Definetly would recommend to all ages.  Throughly enjoyed!

Because it is a real situation in the lives of many especially among teenagers who are trying to find themselves. My thirteen year old daughter and myself were deeply touched and motivated by the plot of this great movie. Stay blessed.
Message is outstanding. The acting was a little hokey. As a family we sat and watched and enjoyed the movie.

The entertainment industry.  Fascinating to almost everyone nowadays, especially the young ones.  This movie is about letting go and trusting God.  He has a plan, and some times it's a bumpy road, but you just have to trust HIM.  This was fantastic, and I plan on having my children watch when they are a little older, I think 7 is a bit too young, 10 should be fine; there are some adult topics, but nothing too racy. It really shows how the industry manipulates people and molds them into what 'they' want them to be. It also teaches parents, that if you have done your job in introducing your child to God and the morals he wants us to uphold, God will shine through in the roughest of times for your kids.

Grace's struggle with God in this movie is relatable, she wants to 'shine' and be herself.  Her father wants to shield her from all the wrong he has already experienced and bottomed out in.  There comes a time in every young person's life when they want to be themselves, and not who anyone else wants them to be, but being yourself and being someone molded in the industry are different.  Being a mother, I can see how I would behave the way the father in this movie would, and it has given me insight into what might be a better method, and that having FAITH(not just saying you do) will help with your own sanity.  Sometimes it is better to let go, and be there to catch them if they fall.

I highly recommend this movie for older children and parents, as a family, it can really open up discussion. It gives a good perspective to children as well, letting them know that parents don't just want to cramp their style, they just don't want to see their children broken.

We all know the cliche Christian films and there's nothing wrong with that. What I love about this movie is that it resonates with ANYONE.  We all face this challenge in life.  Who/what are we chasing after?  Parent-child relationships can be complicated and this story touches upon this perfectly in a way that may still be hard to swallow.  God's grace is sufficient to see us through and we have to trust him with our lives and the lives of those we love.  I actually rented this and am on here to buy it so I can share it with my women's ministry.

This story represents the decisions teens go through and how important the parent child relationship is. It also shows how Hollywood and fame can destroy a persons life. It's not about the person. They become an object for gain.

A great family movie.  The story line is very relevant.  Young girl want to go out and become a star and her parents want her to go college.  What makes this story different is how they relate because of their faith.  Great acting, well done movie.
Need more Christian movies like this. Great story, good acting, and inspirational music. A must watch for the whole family.
Grace Unplugged isn't going to win any oscars but if you are a Christian you will enjoy it. Story line is a little weak but the main actress does a very good job portraying Grace.

I loved the story. We all try to smother our kids and we feel like we are protecting them. It is when we give them back to God that He can begin his work in them.

Great for teens.

as the other reviewer said , I also wanted to like this movie, but I got 15 minutes in & found the conflict between parent & almost adult child to be what is always is. Yelling, going back & forth etc...A little too much generically, real to be entertaining. I parented teens,so been there, done that, don't need or want to revisit that ! I skipped ahead in the movie & the plot moved on predictably, which isn't necessarily a bad thing, but what was presented wasn't very engaging. Also, Oddly, there was the same song, over, & over, OVER again throughout the movie...& not one sung by the girl, but by a guy...the story is about, Grace, so they should have had at least a girl singer, especially since the actress playing Grace DOES sing ! The bulk of the story was a depressing cautionary tale, but you know there's a happy ending. I'd like to see a story about people who make good choices for the right reasons because they have seen what the consequences are second hand. A redemptive story is nice, but this seemed mostly depressing until the end. It's a 'movie'...which to be entertaining benefits from a mix of happy, sad, cautionary & upbeat, maybe a little fun thrown in... Entertainment with a moral, please!
Awesome movie with a solid message.  Reminds us to consider the things that matter most in our lives.  It teaches us a good life lesson.
I thought the movies was really good but it did not play well on amazon and I had to restart it several times.

Thought this film was extremely well-done.  It is also good to see those in Hollywood willing to make films with strong messages of the Christian faith, presented in a way that is not insulting to that faith.
I watched this movie and I loved it, I wish there would be a second movie to it though.! Thanks

Grace Unplugged was an excellent movie for parents and youth. It is a story that left me encouraged and I am planning to watch it again with my daughter. A story full of faith, grace, and God's amazing love at work.
I really wanted to like this more than I did. It was just an okay movie for me. I am happy I rented it but it would not be a movie I would buy. Good message but a little on the boring side.

The age old battle of teenagers and parents is not very different in a Christian home unfortunately.  Even those in ministry don't have a "magic formula" to raise their children and with all the outside influences these days it is a battleground much of the time because neither side is willing to actually communicate.  I found the movie very real because without seeing any situation through the eyes of Christ, it is a battle of flesh and blood and that is a losing battle.  But as soon as one can distance themselves and honestly accept their role in the problem and deal with it, God can and will bring restoration.  I gave it a high rating because it is entertaining but I also believe it has a message for families that can bring healing.
I really enjoyed this movie. The acting was good. The themes dealt with were good. I really enjoyed it and was not disappointed.

My 2 daughters were really touched deeply by this movie.  This is a movie for every parent to watch with their young teens.  I think watching it at an earlier pre-teen age will have more effect on the tweens, then waiting too long.  Great movie!

We're in that period of transition with my oldest daughter, the struggle of letting her grow up and still wanting her to be my little girl. This was the perfect girls night movie for us, it encouraged my daughter in owning her own faith and stengthening her resolve to live for Christ and at the same time drawing her back to a relationship with me as good ole' mom which has been a little rocky with the influx of her making some of her own choices and me not wanting to let her make those choices. It has lots of things to talk about in regards to all the temptations and troubles that our kids are going to be faced with in this world. Delicately done in such a way that it is balanced and shows the world's side without being to overly wordly to the point that you're cringing at the exposure (trying to explain this is hard....I'm just thankful there wasn't an overload of immodesty, drunkedness and sex - they hit on these things enough to make it believable but yet discretely enough to not compromise our experience as viewers). This one will definately be going into our movie collection!

My kids and I loved this movie. We had a great discussion after the movie about not compromising our faith and how easy it is in our society. Great story, wonderful acting and amazing music. We loved it.

Good movie overall.  I kind of expected the story line to develop more regarding her career/ challenges and the decisions she would have to make in the end. I feel that part could have been more developed, but I am glad to see Christian based films available for viewing. I did like the twist at the end regarding the record label.

This was a great film for parents to watch with their teens.  It shows the struggles that young adults have when they go off on their own and the temptations they face that are put in front of them every day. And for parents, it is a reminder that when kids leave home, they are out of our hands but they are in the hands of God and that He is ultimately in control.  Okay, as the mother of one who has left the nest and another who is getting ready to launch, maybe I was a little extra emotional.  I cried more than once during this movie, but they were "good" cries.  Great movie.

The best family movie I have seen in a long time.
This bought tears to us, we are really glad I bought
it for a great price. the quality is terrific and pristine
in HD. Also can share this with our church and other friends
who likes inspiration and motivation.

Highly recommended!

We went to see Grace Unplugged at the movies.  When we left, the kids were downloading the mp3 songs, and we had decided we would own this movie.  I preordered it so I would have it the moment it became available.  It is such a good movie of how a good girl can get offtrack, and why.  Also a good story of love and forgiveness.

I wanted to see this while it was in the movie theater, but it was pulled before I had a chance to see it. I bought the book version and it held true in translation. Perfect for a family movie night and offers a glimpse of the entertainment industry and the trappings it has. I give it two thumbs up
Looking forward to seeing this movie.  I will watch tonight after praise practice after Criminals Minds is over of course.

Excellent Christian movie. The actress portraying Grace is so pretty as well as her singing. Wish there were more movies similar to this one. Thank you for making it available to watch online. Sincerely-faithnancyjo@aol.com
Great wholesome movie with a good lesson for all ages. It has good christian music with recognizable talented young actors.
This is a great movie that deals with real life issues. Real people become real Christians, and every person is a fallen sinner who needs the Grace of God. Romans 3:23 6:23 10:9,10 11:6.
Great movie, excellent plot and the WHOLE family enjoyed it!  Very encouraging and very relevant to our time -- A must see!
Hit home for me ! Well done, great music as well.  Makes you want to hug your teenagers one more time.

Mainstream movie reviewers give this movie weak reviews while they sing the praises of Hollywood standard fare involving profanity, sex, drugs, blood, violence, and general perversity. This is a quality movie with a great and heartening message in the midst of a fallen and lost world. Good music as well. Christian movies like this one get the expected poor treatment by the MSM for obvious reasons, but blessings come through persecution - that we know. We also know that when a movie gets this kind of criticism from the world that the movie's message must be right on target after all. Keep on keeping on. There's a great prize that awaits. I highly recommend this movie, and am thankful for it and others like it. Keep em coming.

I do want to add, though, that the only element I saw lacking in the movie came in the Christian characters frequently seeming to be shy in expressing and explaining their decisions and their faith to the non-believers in the movie. The dad, for instance, turning down the offer for a new recording deal without clearly explaining why to Mossy. Also, there were some missed opportunities to clarify for people the difference between religion and having a relationship with Jesus. Nonetheless the overall message of the movie was clearly expressed, and it is a very important one indeed. It still merits five stars in my view.

This is a great movie! It provided insight into two different perspectives: a young person aspiring to have worldly success; and a parent seeking to provide his child with godly guidance. This movie highlights the facts that fulfillment only comes from Christ and that God is in control, even when it doesn't seem like it. Check it out!
I waited two months to finally watch it, it definetly had some unexpected twists and turns for me. but i liked the message.

I loved this movie!  It was great to watch a movie with my daughters who are 9 and feel good about it!  Some of the situations were a touch old for them, but they are nearing that age where we need to engage in conversation about these situations anyway.  (Whether  i want to or not!!! :I ) I loved that wrong was made right and God was glorified in this movie!
This an excellent family values movie. Teens should especially see this.  Good entertainment!  We loved it and highly recommend it.
I was touched by this movie and it made me sincerely cry. I watched it with my 11 year old daughter and I felt so good watching such a good moral, spiritual, impacting movie with her.

It gives starry eyed teenage singers that want to go big the realities of the entertainment world. It's glamour has a price. Grace, under pressure, comprised her values and almost made some life changing choices. She eventually with the help of a Christian friend was able to see the devastating choices she was making.

What a refreshing movie!! Great songs, and the actors/actresses they chose we perfect! It shows what happens when focusing on the world rather then God.. the world is so corrupt, we have to make sure we stay in the word!  Thank you Jesus for your constant guidance, love, strength,and forgiveness! What an awesome God we have!!
Because I love the Movies that are good and encouraging especially that glorify God and His ways . Love spiritual, uplifting movies..
This movie reminds us that God is always with us even when we go astray! Great family movie to watch

An enjoyable, engaging and moving story that exceeds expectations.

An uplifting and absorbing story that the whole family can watch.

I highly recommend this movie.  Great for a date night, or family movie night.
This is a heart-touching film that is perfect for parents and teens to see together.  We saw it in the cinema and are looking forward to getting it on blu-ray when it comes out in February!
This was one of the best movies I've seen I a very long time. It has a wonderful message of love, forgiveness and redemption!!! A must have movie!!!

Such a feel good movie. I loved this movie and if you have teenagers you should take them to see this or buy it and have the family watch it together. Best movie ever and I can totally relate having a teenager myself. You can't go wrong with this movie!
this movie touched something deep inside of me. saw it first with my wife. saw it again with the family. can't wait for DVD. acting is superb. music is riveting. story line is so real.

Unlike some other faith based films released this story has the ability to hold your attention and delight you with a well written screenplay while delivering a heart warming message. Entertaining for adults and safe to watch with kids! A great pick for a family movie that you won't be tempted to check your Facebook while watching.
Loved it!  AJ is so talented as an actress, but also has a GREAT voice!  Make sure you have the tissues handy, too!
Incredible movie! So many messages to encourage.  God's protection. God's grace. God's goodness. Redemption. Can't wait to get it on dvd.

Loved this movie.  Very well made and my daughter loved it too.  We plan on getting the DVD when it comes out!!!

I watched this with my daughters...and am so glad I did. It has a fantastic message and I was impressed with the acting. Things weren't candy coated and I liked the realism...yet the movie provided hope. Loved the message of making good choices and that this movie and its impactful message was such a great influence on my tweens.

Great movie!!
